Problem Set 2 Solutions

Question 1

Suppose \(Y_i = {\bf I}_p X_1 + (1-{\bf I}_p) X_2\) for \(i=1,\ldots,n\), where the indicator function is defined as \[\begin{align} {\bf I}_p & = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{with probability } p \\ 0 & \text{with probability } 1-p\end{cases} \end{align}\] and where \(p = \frac{1}{3}\), \(X_1 \sim N(\mu_1,1)\), and \(X_1 \sim N(\mu_2,1)\). That is, the random variables \(\{Y_i\}\) are drawn from a discrete mixture of Normals.

a. (10 points)

Write the join density function for \(\{Y_i\}\).

Solution:

The univariate density for \(Y_i\) is \[\begin{align} f_{Y_i}(y_i|\mu_1,\mu_2) & = p \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\} + (1-p) \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}, \,\, \text{for} \,\, i = 1,\ldots,n. \end{align}\] Thus, the joint density is \[\begin{align} f_{{\bf Y}}({\bf y}|\mu_1,\mu_2) & = \prod_{i=1}^n f_{Y_i}(y_i|p,\mu_1,\mu_2) \\ & = \frac{1}{(2\pi)^{n/2}} \prod_{i=1}^n \left(p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\} + (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}\right). \end{align}\]

b. (10 points)

What is the log likelihood?

Solution:

\[\begin{align} \ell(\mu_1,\mu_2|{\bf y}) & = \log(f_{{\bf Y}}({\bf y}|\mu_1,\mu_2)) \\ & = -\frac{n}{2} \log(2\pi) + \sum_{i=1}^n \log\left(p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\} + (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}\right). \end{align}\]

c. (15 points)

What are the gradient and hessian of the log likelihood?

Solution:

\[\begin{align} {\bf g}(\mu_1,\mu_2|{\bf y}) & = \left[\begin{array}{c} \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \mu_1} \\ \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \mu_2}\end{array}\right] \\ & = \sum_{i=1}^n \left[\begin{array}{c} \frac{(y_i-\mu_1) p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\}}{p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\} + (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}} \\ \frac{(y_i-\mu_2) (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}}{p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\} + (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}}\end{array} \right]. \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} {\bf H}(\mu_1,\mu_2|{\bf y}) & = \left[\begin{array}{cc} \frac{\partial^2 \ell}{\partial \mu_1^2} & \frac{\partial^2 \ell}{\partial \mu_1 \partial \mu_2} \\ \frac{\partial^2 \ell}{\partial \mu_1 \partial \mu_2} & \frac{\partial^2 \ell}{\partial \mu_2^2}\end{array}\right] \\ & = \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{\mathcal{V}_1 \mathcal{V}_2}{\mathcal{V}_1 + \mathcal{V}_2}\left[\begin{array}{cc} (y_i-\mu_1)^2-1 - \frac{\mathcal{V}_1}{\mathcal{V}_2} & -(y_i-\mu_1)(y_i-\mu_2) \\ -(y_i-\mu_1)(y_i-\mu_2) & (y_i-\mu_2)^2-1 - \frac{\mathcal{V}_2}{\mathcal{V}_1} \end{array} \right], \end{align}\] where \(\mathcal{V}_1 = p \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_1)^2\right\}\) and \(\mathcal{V}_2 = (1-p) \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} (y_i-\mu_2)^2\right\}\).

d. (15 points)

Using the simulated data on the course website, compute maximum likelihood estimates of \(\mu_1\) ane \(\mu_2\) using the Newton-Raphson method.

Solution:

Using the code below, it is possible to show that Newton-Raphson is sensitive to the starting values for \(\mu_1\) and \(\mu_2\). To get reasonable guesses for the starting values, we can plot a histogram or kernel density estimate (essentially smoothed histogram) of the data:

y = read.csv('ps2Data.csv')$x
plot(density(y))

Since there are two peaks in the vicinity of 2.5 and 5.5, we choose these as our starting values. The Newton-Raphson method is, in fact, slightly unstable, often resulting in a non-invertible hessian. To improve convergence, we can attenuate the hessian at each step with a scale factor – in this case, I have chose 0.2.

tol = 1e-2
tau = 2*tol
p = 1/3
mu0 = c(1,7)
while(tau > tol){
  V1 = p*exp(-0.5*(y-mu0[1])^2)
  V2 = (1-p)*exp(-0.5*(y-mu0[2])^2)
  gradient = c(sum((y-mu0[1])*V1/(V1+V2)),sum((y-mu0[2])*V2/(V1+V2)))
  H11 = sum((((y-mu0[1])^2-1)*V1*V2-V1^2)/(V1+V2))
  H12 = sum(-(y-mu0[1])*(y-mu0[2])*V1*V2/(V1+V2))
  H22 = sum((((y-mu0[2])^2-1)*V1*V2-V2^2)/(V1+V2))
  hessian = matrix(c(H11,H12,H12,H22),ncol=2)
  mu1 = mu0 - 0.2*solve(hessian)%*%gradient
  tau = max(abs(mu1-mu0))
  mu0 = mu1
}
print(mu0)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 2.730306
## [2,] 5.422600

Question 2 (15 points)

Assume the following linear model: \[\begin{align} Y & = \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \varepsilon, \,\,\, \varepsilon \sim N(0,\sigma^2). \end{align}\]

a. (10 points)

Write the expression for the best linear predictor, \(\boldsymbol{\beta}^* = (\beta_1,\beta_2)\), with each element of the associated matrices and vectors individually specified.

Solution:

From the lecture notes, we know that \[\begin{align} \boldsymbol{\beta}^* & = \text{E}\left[\bf{X}\bf{X}'\right]^{-1} \text{E}\left[{\bf X} Y\right] \\ & = \text{E}\left[\begin{array}{cc} X_1 X_1 & X_1 X_2 \\ X_2 X_1 & X_2 X_2 \end{array}\right]^{-1} \text{E}\left[\begin{array}{c} X_1 Y \\ X_2 Y \end{array}\right] \\ & = \left[\begin{array}{cc} \text{E}[X_1^2] & \text{E}[X_1 X_2] \\ \text{E}[X_2 X_1] & \text{E}[X_2^2] \end{array}\right]^{-1} \left[\begin{array}{c} \text{E}[X_1 Y] \\ \text{E}[X_2 Y] \end{array}\right] \\ & = \frac{1}{\text{E}[X_1^2] \text{E}[X_2^2] - 2 \text{E}[X_1 X_2]} \left[\begin{array}{cc} \text{E}[X_2^2] & -\text{E}[X_1 X_2] \\ -\text{E}[X_2 X_1] & \text{E}[X_1^2] \end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{c} \text{E}[X_1 Y] \\ \text{E}[X_2 Y] \end{array}\right] \\ & = \left[\begin{array}{c} \frac{\text{E}[X_2^2] \text{E}[X_1 Y] - \text{E}[X_1 X_2] \text{E}[X_2 Y]}{\text{E}[X_1^2] \text{E}[X_2^22] - 2 \text{E}[X_1 X_2]} \\ \frac{\text{E}[X_1^2] \text{E}[X_2 Y] - \text{E}[X_1 X_2] \text{E}[X_1 Y]}{\text{E}[X_1^2] \text{E}[X_2^2] - 2 \text{E}[X_1 X_2]} \end{array}\right]. \end{align}\]

b. (10 points)

Suppose you have \(n\) obersvations of \((Y,X_1,X_2)\), collected in vectors \({\bf y}' = (y_1,\ldots,y_n)\), \({\bf x}_1' = (x_{11},\ldots,x_{1n})\), and\({\bf x}_2' = (x_{21},\ldots,x_{2n})\). Write the expression for the least-squares estimator \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\), with each element of the associated matrices and vectors individually specified.

Solution:

Setting \({\bf X} = [{\bf x}_1 \,\, {\bf x}_2]\), the formula for the least-squares estimator is \[\begin{align} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} & = \left[{\bf X}' {\bf X}\right]^{-1} {\bf X}' {\bf y} \\ & = \left[\begin{array}{cc} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 & \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} x_{2i} \\ \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} x_{1i} & \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 \end{array}\right]^{-1} \left[\begin{array}{c} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} y_i \\ \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} y_i\end{array}\right] \\ & = \frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 - 2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}x_{2i}} \left[\begin{array}{cc} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 & -\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} x_{2i} \\ -\sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} x_{1i} & \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{c} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} y_i \\ \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} y_i\end{array}\right] \\ & = \left[\begin{array}{c} \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} y_i -\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} x_{2i} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} y_i}{\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 - 2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}x_{2i}} \\ \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} y_i -\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} x_{2i} \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} y_i}{\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 - 2 \sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}x_{2i}}\end{array}\right]. \end{align}\]

c. (10 points)

How are the solutions to (a) and (b) related?

Solution:

Under fairly week conditions, the weak law of large numbers will apply to each of the sums in the solution to (b), resulting in \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i}^2 \stackrel{p}{\to} E[X_1^2]\), \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i}^2 \stackrel{p}{\to} E[X_2^2]\), \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} x_{2i} \stackrel{p}{\to} E[X_1 X_2]\), \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{1i} y_i \stackrel{p}{\to} E[X_1 Y]\), and \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{2i} y_i \stackrel{p}{\to} E[X_2 Y]\), as \(n \to \infty\). As a consequence, \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \stackrel{p}{\to} \boldsymbol{\beta}^*\).

Question 3

Download data for the CME Group Nasdaq 100 futures front-month contract for the period 1 Apr 2008 to 31 Mar 2018. This data can be obtained from Quandl via the symbol NQ1.

a. (10 points)

Using daily returns, compute monthly realized variance by summing the squared returns within each month: \(RV_t = \sum_{i=1}^n r_{t+i}^2\), where \(t\) denotes the month, \(i\) indexes the days within the month, and \(n\) represents the number of trading days in the month (typically around 22). Plot the time series of realized variance.

Solution:

library(Quandl)
library(quantmod)
library(data.table)
NQ1 = Quandl("CHRIS/CME_NQ1",start_date="2008-01-04",end_date="2018-03-31",type="xts")
nqRets = dailyReturn(NQ1$Settle)
nqRetsTable = data.table(index(nqRets),nqRets,year(index(nqRets)),month(index(nqRets)))
colnames(nqRetsTable) = c("date","returns","year","month")
rvTable = nqRetsTable[,.(sum(returns^2)),by=.(year,month)]
rv = as.xts(rvTable$V1,order.by=as.Date(paste0(as.character(rvTable$year),"/",as.character(rvTable$month),"/01")))
colnames(rv) = "RV"
plot(rv,type='l')

b. (10 points)

Find the best fitting ARMA model for the log of realized variance. Report the parameter estimates and standard errors and provide some interpretation.

Solution:

A sample ACF plot of the realized variance suggests that an appropriate model might be an \(MA(2)\), since the estimated autocorrelations are no longer significant after lag 2:

acf(rv)

The estimated \(MA(2)\) results in the following coefficients and standard errors:

estOut = arima(rv,order=c(0,0,2))
#summary(estOut)
estOut$coef
##         ma1         ma2   intercept 
## 0.700041242 0.211905374 0.003871607
sqrt(diag(estOut$var.coef))
##         ma1         ma2   intercept 
## 0.083445936 0.092830651 0.001041362

which are significant at the 5% level. A residual plot suggests that the model is somewhat lacking:

plot(estOut$residuals)

Clearly, the residuals suggest a poor fit. In fact, the original plot of the data suggests that they are not stationary – the variance of RV is clearly not constant throught time. Further, RV is a strictly positive variable, which is not appropriate for an \(ARMA\) model (where the shocks, and hence the response variable, are allowed to be negative). One possibility is to consider a model for the log of RV:

plot(log(rv))

\(\log(RV)\) looks like a more appropriate input for an \(ARMA\) model. Recomputing the sample ACF:

acf(log(rv))

Which suggests that the data have at least one \(AR\) component. In fact the function auto.arima selects an \(ARMA(1,1)\) model for the first differences of \(\log(RV)\), but since I have no theoretical reason to believe we should take first differences, I constrain the \(d\) parameter in the \(ARIMA\) model to be zero:

library(forecast)
logEstOut = auto.arima(log(rv),max.d=0)
logEstOut

The resulting residuals look much better:

plot(logEstOut$residuals)

acf(logEstOut$residuals)
